WEBVTT

00:02.280 --> 00:04.600
TOMMY: <i>I intend to do business
with Billy Kimber.</i>

00:04.680 --> 00:05.760
-(GUNSHOT)
-(WOMAN SCREAMING)

00:05.840 --> 00:08.240
Is there any man here named Shelby?

00:08.320 --> 00:11.080
TOMMY: <i>I'm planning an expansion
onto the racetracks.</i>

00:11.280 --> 00:14.120
It would be an hon our
to work with you, Mr Kimber.

00:14.320 --> 00:18.520
Nobody works "with" me.
People work "for" me.

00:18.840 --> 00:21.680
TOMMY: <i>Danny, you're a good man
and a good soldier.</i>

00:21.760 --> 00:23.440
Yes, Sergeant Major.

00:23.520 --> 00:25.320
(SCREAMING)

00:26.520 --> 00:29.320
Freddie Thorne is at the very top
of my list.

00:29.400 --> 00:33.280
Well, cross him off.
He won't be returning to the city.

00:33.800 --> 00:35.080
THORNE: <i>We're not going anywhere, Ada.</i>

00:35.320 --> 00:37.840
We're gonna stay here, we're gonna
marry here, with our baby.

00:37.960 --> 00:40.280
<i>I'm not afraid of Tommy Shelby.</i>

00:40.600 --> 00:44.240
Thomas, you sell those guns to anyone
who has use to them, you will hang.

00:44.680 --> 00:46.720
POLLY: <i>Dump them somewhere
the police can find them.</i>

00:47.000 --> 00:48.400
No.

00:48.760 --> 00:52.960
Thomas Shelby is now the beginning,
the middle and the end of your mission.

00:53.040 --> 00:54.080
So what shall I do?

00:54.920 --> 00:58.720
CAMPBELL: <i>You must do
everything you can to get close to him.</i>

00:59.320 --> 01:02.240
Dig out a nice dress,
I want to take you to the races.

01:02.400 --> 01:04.880
I warn you, I'll break your heart.

01:06.080 --> 01:07.680
Already broken.

01:17.800 --> 01:19.560
(PEOPLE CHATTING)

01:23.880 --> 01:28.840
<i># Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track</i>

01:31.600 --> 01:35.840
<i># Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

01:35.920 --> 01:39.200
<i># As it shifts and cracks</i>

01:39.920 --> 01:46.360
<i># Where secrets lie in the border fires
in the humming wires</i>

01:46.440 --> 01:51.480
<i># Hey man, you know
you're never coming back #</i>

01:51.560 --> 01:52.840
Morning, sir.

01:56.840 --> 02:00.600
<i># On a gathering storm comes
a tall handsome man</i>

02:00.680 --> 02:03.440
<i># In a dusty black coat with
a red right hand #</i>

02:03.520 --> 02:05.040
(KNOCK <i>AT</i> DOOR)

02:05.120 --> 02:07.600
Give me a bottle of whisky
and three glasses, please.

02:07.680 --> 02:09.560
-Scotch or Irish?
-Irish.

02:12.280 --> 02:15.800
I've decided not to go to the races.

02:15.920 --> 02:17.320
Not unless you give me another two pound

02:17.400 --> 02:18.640
ten shilling towards the dress.

02:20.160 --> 02:21.480
I've already given you three.

02:21.680 --> 02:23.600
How much did you pay for the suit
you'll be wearing?

02:24.200 --> 02:27.200
Oh, I don't pay for suits.
My suits are on the house.

02:27.280 --> 02:28.560
Or the house burns down.

02:30.360 --> 02:32.320
So, you want me to go
looking like a flower girl?

02:33.240 --> 02:35.840
-What I want makes no difference.
-(GLASSES CLINKING)

02:39.080 --> 02:41.040
It's not me you're dressing up for.

03:11.440 --> 03:14.920
You'll forgive me, Mr Shelby,
if I indulge a little bit?

03:15.000 --> 03:16.400
Please.

03:17.160 --> 03:19.160
It takes a lot for a man from Sparkbrook

03:19.240 --> 03:21.120
to step inside this pub.
(CHUCKLES)

03:21.720 --> 03:25.080
Anyone with money and good intentions
is welcome at The Garrison.

03:26.480 --> 03:27.720
(MATCH STRIKING)

03:28.600 --> 03:31.640
Now, you said you had business.

03:35.760 --> 03:37.440
It's delicate, Mr Shelby.

03:38.520 --> 03:41.200
It's a question
of who knows what about what.

03:42.880 --> 03:45.760
Concerns the factory
down the road at the BSA.

03:47.640 --> 03:51.360
Now, as you might know,
most of the paint shop there is Irish.

03:52.160 --> 03:55.440
Big old place like that,
rumours get started.

03:55.520 --> 03:57.320
Rumours that there was a robbery.

04:00.320 --> 04:01.520
Robbery of what?

04:02.120 --> 04:04.080
MAN: Guns, Mr Shelby.

04:04.480 --> 04:06.480
A serious amount of guns.

04:08.520 --> 04:10.120
TOMMY: And what business
is that of mine?

04:10.560 --> 04:14.400
When it comes to speculation,
you can't beat a factory night shift.

04:15.160 --> 04:17.640
Some say there was word from the
proofing bay

04:18.480 --> 04:20.360
it was the Peaky Blinders
that took them.

04:22.480 --> 04:24.240
Your night shift must be dreaming.

04:24.320 --> 04:25.920
-Maybe they are.
-Maybe they're not.

04:26.560 --> 04:28.920
What we're trying to say is, Mr Shelby,

04:29.760 --> 04:33.400
that if you were to hear about
the whereabouts of said items,

04:34.720 --> 04:36.000
we'd pay good money.

04:36.080 --> 04:39.240
-You have good money?
-We have the collections from the pubs.

04:39.840 --> 04:41.840
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

04:42.440 --> 04:44.040
-For who do you speak?
-The people of Ireland.

04:44.120 --> 04:46.080
The Irish Republican Army.

04:46.640 --> 04:48.880
-For a fact?
-For a fucking fact.

04:54.480 --> 04:55.960
You think we're jokers?

04:56.960 --> 04:58.480
Am I laughing?

05:02.160 --> 05:07.880
<i># Oh, father, why are you so sad</i>

05:08.920 --> 05:12.960
<i># On this bright Easter morn #</i>

05:13.040 --> 05:14.280
Maguire, will you shut up?

05:14.840 --> 05:19.920
<i># When Irishmen are proud and glad</i>

05:20.520 --> 05:24.080
<i># Of the land where they were born #</i>

05:24.160 --> 05:26.320
Maguire, away and shite.
We're trying to talk business here.

05:26.400 --> 05:30.480
<i># Oh, Son, I see sad memories view</i>

05:31.280 --> 05:35.120
<i># Of far.off distant days</i>

05:36.480 --> 05:41.400
<i># When, being just a boy like you,</i>

05:42.240 --> 05:48.680
<i># I joined the IRA #</i>

05:50.600 --> 05:51.680
Bravo.

05:52.720 --> 05:54.560
<i># Where are the lads who stood with me #</i>

05:54.640 --> 05:56.280
TOMMY: All right, boys.

05:56.360 --> 05:58.360
<i># When history was made #</i>

05:58.440 --> 06:00.800
If I hear anything about who know what
about what, I'll let you know.

06:00.880 --> 06:05.240
<i># I long to see the boys
of the old IRA #</i>

06:08.560 --> 06:11.040
I thought you only allowed
singing on Saturday.

06:12.000 --> 06:13.480
Whisky's good proofing water.

06:14.080 --> 06:15.760
Tells you who's real and who isn't.

06:15.920 --> 06:17.640
And what did my countrymen want?

06:17.720 --> 06:19.160
Oh, they're nobodies.

06:20.040 --> 06:21.880
They drink in The Black Swan
in Sparkbrook.

06:22.440 --> 06:24.720
They're only rebels because
they like the songs.

06:25.640 --> 06:26.720
You have sympathies with them?

06:27.360 --> 06:29.080
I have no sympathies of any description.

06:29.640 --> 06:32.120
Their accents are so thick,
it's a wonder you could understand them.

06:32.560 --> 06:34.480
Next time, I could translate.

06:34.840 --> 06:36.000
You would work for me?

06:37.400 --> 06:38.480
I thought I already was.

06:39.280 --> 06:40.880
So you are coming to the races.

06:43.240 --> 06:45.240
Two pounds, ten shillings.

06:49.080 --> 06:50.280
Ten shillings.

06:51.800 --> 06:53.200
Buy something red.

06:53.400 --> 06:54.760
To match his handkerchief.

06:55.200 --> 06:56.640
Whose handkerchief?

07:21.200 --> 07:22.440
Ada, what the hell?

07:22.800 --> 07:24.920
I dared myself to run
through their territory in my dress.

07:25.440 --> 07:26.720
-Are you mad?
-Yeah.

07:26.840 --> 07:28.520
Mad as hell with all of them.

07:28.600 --> 07:30.160
I love you.

07:32.320 --> 07:33.480
I love you, too.

07:33.760 --> 07:35.760
The more they try and stop us,
the madder I'll be.

07:35.960 --> 07:38.640
-Come on, princess. The vicar's waiting.
-Wait.

07:39.720 --> 07:41.560
How do I look?

07:46.280 --> 07:47.720
Like an angel.

08:03.240 --> 08:04.560
Moss,

08:05.680 --> 08:07.920
what do we know about The Black Swan?

08:08.560 --> 08:10.840
An operative has provided intelligence

08:11.960 --> 08:14.640
and it is a place where IRA men gather.

08:14.840 --> 08:19.000
It's just a lot of drunken navigators
singing songs, sir.

08:19.080 --> 08:21.000
The IRA wouldn't go near them.

08:21.760 --> 08:24.040
Then why are two of them
looking to buy guns?

08:26.640 --> 08:28.120
Do you have names?

08:29.840 --> 08:31.760
Must she do everything for you?

08:32.200 --> 08:33.400
She, sir?

08:33.480 --> 08:37.080
One female operative
has proved more useful

08:38.120 --> 08:40.480
than any of you great lumps of men.

08:41.680 --> 08:45.720
We are regular police officers, sir,
not spies.

08:46.600 --> 08:48.840
We can only act when
a crime has been committed.

08:49.320 --> 08:52.960
Perhaps I should send some men down
to The Black Swan to ask questions.

08:53.200 --> 08:54.960
And scare them all into hiding?

08:55.840 --> 08:57.560
Not the best of tactics, Sergeant.

08:58.040 --> 09:01.000
My tactics come from
my experiences in France.

09:01.960 --> 09:06.440
Most of my great lumps of men
served in France too, sir.

09:08.640 --> 09:12.640
I serve my country every day.

09:13.520 --> 09:15.040
That'll be all, Sergeant.

10:06.040 --> 10:07.560
Away and shite.

10:44.760 --> 10:46.400
Fancy me, do you?

10:47.840 --> 10:49.200
What are you?

10:49.480 --> 10:50.720
Copper?

10:53.200 --> 10:54.760
Proddie bitch!

10:55.720 --> 10:59.200
I've seen you. I've seen your face
serving at The Garrison.

10:59.640 --> 11:01.520
Come here.

11:01.600 --> 11:03.640
I'm taking you in for interrogation.

11:04.040 --> 11:06.080
On behalf of the Irish Free State.

11:08.040 --> 11:09.800
(GUNSHOT)

11:32.480 --> 11:33.800
All right?

11:35.560 --> 11:36.840
Are you armed?

11:39.120 --> 11:40.200
No.

11:42.040 --> 11:43.400
Then I'll tell you.

11:45.600 --> 11:47.800
Ada and Freddie Thorne
were married today.

11:48.040 --> 11:49.560
They defied your orders.

11:49.680 --> 11:51.240
They haven't left the city.

11:55.080 --> 11:56.240
(SIGHS)

12:00.560 --> 12:01.840
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

12:03.680 --> 12:05.240
I'll deal with it.

12:08.400 --> 12:09.520
Thomas.

12:10.080 --> 12:11.600
I'll deal with it.

12:12.400 --> 12:13.800
Where are they?

12:14.840 --> 12:17.360
Freddie's comrades have safe houses.
Why do you want to know?

12:17.440 --> 12:19.560
I want to send them flowers.
Why do you think?

12:19.840 --> 12:21.560
Would it be so bad if they stayed?

12:23.720 --> 12:25.720
I promised I'd run Freddie out of town.

12:28.200 --> 12:29.560
Promised who?

12:40.680 --> 12:42.640
I told the coppers Freddie
wouldn't come back.

12:43.680 --> 12:46.240
-It was part of the deal.
-What bloody deal?

12:47.000 --> 12:50.280
What happened to family votes?
What happened to meetings?

12:52.840 --> 12:56.920
If you let me deal with Ada and Freddie,
it'll end in peace.

13:00.280 --> 13:02.280
Christ knows you've had
your fill of war.

13:07.960 --> 13:09.680
You get Freddie out of town, Pol.

13:10.520 --> 13:12.320
Or else I'll deal with it myself.

13:17.840 --> 13:19.360
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

13:26.280 --> 13:27.600
(RETCHES)

13:29.800 --> 13:31.200
(COUGHS)

13:37.040 --> 13:38.160
(SHUDDERS)

14:10.360 --> 14:13.280
MOSS: The victim had been drinking
in The Black Swan pub, sir.

14:13.520 --> 14:15.200
The pub that you told me about.

14:15.800 --> 14:18.880
And the neighbour said that she saw
a young woman leaving the street

14:18.960 --> 14:20.840
where the body was found.

14:22.000 --> 14:23.320
A woman, sir.

14:24.040 --> 14:25.760
I was wondering if
there was a connection.

14:26.320 --> 14:28.720
A connection with what, Sergeant?

14:29.320 --> 14:32.240
You said that your spy was a woman, sir.

14:32.880 --> 14:34.920
I wondered if there was now a policy.

14:38.800 --> 14:40.160
Shoot to kill.

14:40.760 --> 14:42.480
Like there was in Belfast.

14:45.040 --> 14:47.120
Republicans are famously factional.

14:48.440 --> 14:50.560
He was killed by one of his own.

14:53.120 --> 14:54.680
That'll be all, Sergeant.

14:56.880 --> 14:59.080
And they're not called spies.

14:59.480 --> 15:00.840
They're called operatives.

15:01.200 --> 15:02.960
Operatives, sir. Right, sir.

15:07.600 --> 15:08.840
THORNE: It's how you say things.

15:08.920 --> 15:10.040
ADA: Yeah.

15:12.920 --> 15:14.880
THORNE: What the bloody hell
is she doing here?

15:15.880 --> 15:18.000
200 pounds, Freddie.

15:19.880 --> 15:21.120
For what?

15:21.640 --> 15:22.880
For us.

15:23.600 --> 15:26.120
For a honeymoon that goes on forever.

15:30.680 --> 15:32.800
-Where did it come from?
-Family fund.

15:33.600 --> 15:35.760
Pockets of widows and desperate men.

15:36.080 --> 15:37.800
See sense, Freddie.

15:37.880 --> 15:39.560
POLLY: Tommy's not gonna let this rest.

15:39.720 --> 15:42.680
Times like these, communists
in the family is bad for business.

15:43.840 --> 15:45.160
You have to leave the city.

15:45.920 --> 15:48.000
You think I can't handle Tommy Shelby?

15:48.240 --> 15:51.560
You can't. I'm having trouble these days
and I'm twice the man you are.

15:51.800 --> 15:52.880
(CHUCKLES)

15:56.080 --> 15:57.440
I went into town.

15:58.680 --> 16:00.080
The Cunard office.

16:01.280 --> 16:03.480
I booked you both tickets
for the next boat

16:03.560 --> 16:04.960
from Liverpool to New York.

16:05.480 --> 16:07.000
ADA: America, Freddie.

16:07.480 --> 16:10.400
They've already had their revolution.
You won't have to bother.

16:17.880 --> 16:20.560
Would you ladies at least let a man
sleep on it?

16:21.560 --> 16:22.720
(SIGHS)

16:53.520 --> 16:55.440
You had no business.

16:59.000 --> 17:01.640
Observe and report,
that is your remit.

17:01.960 --> 17:03.800
I decided we needed to know
where he lived.

17:04.160 --> 17:06.080
I warned you not to let your...

17:06.200 --> 17:08.960
Your personal history
cloud your judgement.

17:09.040 --> 17:10.920
You went after him because he was IRA.

17:11.000 --> 17:14.000
I followed him because
I thought he might have information.

17:14.800 --> 17:18.360
According to the rules, I should pull
you out of Garrison Lane immediately.

17:18.440 --> 17:19.520
No.

17:20.000 --> 17:21.520
Cheltenham's tomorrow.

17:23.160 --> 17:24.960
You take too much upon yourself.

17:27.040 --> 17:29.360
This is an "active military mission".

17:29.440 --> 17:30.800
Your words.

17:30.880 --> 17:32.360
I'm doing my job.

17:32.800 --> 17:33.920
Grace,

17:34.000 --> 17:37.880
the death of a base Fenian
doesn't concern me.

17:37.960 --> 17:39.640
Your welfare does.

17:41.160 --> 17:43.240
Killing a man affects the heart.

17:45.440 --> 17:46.960
And as for my heart...

17:48.040 --> 17:50.240
I know that, because
of our family connections,

17:50.320 --> 17:52.880
you take my progress personally.

17:53.720 --> 17:55.680
But I don't need you to be my father.

17:59.080 --> 18:00.640
I will be thinking of you.

18:13.040 --> 18:14.800
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

18:26.680 --> 18:27.880
Mr Shelby, sir?

18:27.960 --> 18:29.240
Mr Zhang.

18:30.920 --> 18:34.240
That suit is sold, sir.
It's being collected this morning.

18:35.040 --> 18:36.320
I know.

18:42.080 --> 18:43.480
ZHANG: Please, gentlemen,
no fighting in here.

18:43.560 --> 18:46.000
It's all right. I come as a friend.

18:48.240 --> 18:50.520
You're collecting your suit
for Cheltenham. It's very nice.

18:50.920 --> 18:52.080
How the bloody hell do you know?

18:52.680 --> 18:54.640
I know a lot of things, Mr Kimber.

18:55.600 --> 18:58.080
And as I told you before,
I know the Lee brothers.

18:58.960 --> 19:01.240
And I know they're gonna be at
the Cheltenham races as well.

19:01.520 --> 19:03.040
Yes, well they're gonna
lose a lot of money on

19:03.120 --> 19:04.760
fast women and slow nags.

19:04.840 --> 19:07.640
No. They're planning
on showing up in numbers

19:07.720 --> 19:10.200
and robbing your bookies,
running chalk and rafflers.

19:11.080 --> 19:12.880
You think I can't handle the Lees?

19:13.160 --> 19:15.600
Just a word of warning
from a friend. That's all.

19:19.000 --> 19:20.640
TOMMY: I'll see you at Cheltenham.

19:21.040 --> 19:23.320
KIMBER: I'll wave at you from my box.

19:24.160 --> 19:27.120
If you're coming to the races,
bring that pretty barmaid of yours.

19:27.800 --> 19:29.320
Already invited.

19:33.120 --> 19:34.840
MAN 1 : Come on, Freddie.
MAN 2: Comrades.

19:35.120 --> 19:40.760
Comrades, as you know, to even
gather like this today is illegal.

19:41.480 --> 19:43.720
Chief Inspector Campbell has ordered

19:43.800 --> 19:47.400
that we're not allowed to assemble
in groups of more than three people.

19:48.360 --> 19:52.680
So, to comply with the law, please now
clump together in groups of three.

19:52.760 --> 19:54.440
(ALL LAUGHING)

19:56.440 --> 19:58.200
Do you hear that, boys?

19:58.280 --> 20:01.000
The same whistles they used to blow
to send us over the top

20:01.360 --> 20:04.040
they now blow to try and break us up.

20:04.160 --> 20:05.840
So before the Specials get in,

20:06.240 --> 20:09.040
raise your hands
all those who want to strike.

20:09.160 --> 20:11.040
(ALL CHEERING)

20:12.640 --> 20:14.040
Now disperse.

20:14.120 --> 20:16.160
Disperse and take the message home.

20:16.880 --> 20:19.320
United, we will never be defeated.

20:19.480 --> 20:20.560
MAN: Yes! Yes!

20:26.120 --> 20:27.720
(MEN CLAMOURING)

20:29.640 --> 20:31.680
JOHN: Tommy. Oi, Tommy.

20:32.320 --> 20:33.840
What the hell's being happening?

20:34.600 --> 20:36.840
The police have just raided
a rally at the factory.

20:37.320 --> 20:38.800
We're thinking Freddie Thorne's back.

20:38.960 --> 20:40.800
I know he is, and he's with Ada.

20:41.120 --> 20:43.720
How hard can it be to find
the only girl in Birmingham

20:43.800 --> 20:45.120
with four-inch heels, eh?

20:45.360 --> 20:46.680
She's with the commies.

20:46.880 --> 20:49.520
They have little rat holes
all over the city.

20:50.600 --> 20:51.760
Just wanna know where she is.

20:52.440 --> 20:54.280
Tommy, you'd best have a word
with Arthur as well.

20:55.080 --> 20:56.960
What's wrong with bloody Arthur?

20:57.920 --> 20:59.760
He's got the Flanders blues again.

21:39.560 --> 21:43.160
People keep asking me questions
that I don't know the answer to.

21:47.960 --> 21:50.200
Is it true your Ada got married?

21:52.480 --> 21:54.040
I say, "I don't know."

21:56.120 --> 21:57.640
"Where is she living then?"

22:00.240 --> 22:01.760
"I don't know."

22:03.640 --> 22:05.240
"Arthur,

22:07.760 --> 22:10.160
"who killed the Paddy
from The Black Swan?"

22:12.960 --> 22:15.520
I go, "What Paddy?"

22:19.560 --> 22:21.000
They say,

22:22.480 --> 22:24.560
"Is it you Peaky Blinders

22:25.560 --> 22:27.360
"who stole the guns

22:27.960 --> 22:30.080
"from the BSA?"

22:38.000 --> 22:39.840
What guns, Tommy?

22:41.920 --> 22:44.600
Arthur, after your beating,
I thought you needed a break.

22:44.680 --> 22:47.400
(SHOUTING) What bloody guns, Tommy?

22:50.080 --> 22:51.400
Arthur, I was gonna tell you.

22:51.480 --> 22:52.960
You were gonna tell me?

22:53.200 --> 22:55.360
Arthur, listen to me.

22:57.400 --> 23:00.840
You've had a hard time these past
few years. God knows you have.

23:01.600 --> 23:03.480
You deserve some rest.

23:05.240 --> 23:06.960
We had some luck.

23:07.760 --> 23:09.720
Some bloody luck.

23:10.360 --> 23:13.120
It fell off a wagon into our laps.

23:13.560 --> 23:15.400
And all you need to know is,

23:15.480 --> 23:18.520
it's us that has the machine guns now.

23:18.600 --> 23:20.640
And it's them that's in the mud.

23:22.720 --> 23:24.240
All right?

23:31.760 --> 23:33.000
Come on.

23:34.280 --> 23:35.800
I have a surprise for you.

23:36.440 --> 23:37.560
Come on.

24:01.960 --> 24:03.360
ARTHUR: Surprise.

24:03.640 --> 24:05.120
Where is she?

24:07.320 --> 24:10.040
What is it you've always wanted, Arthur?

24:10.480 --> 24:11.560
Eh?

24:12.120 --> 24:14.280
When we were in France, you used to say,

24:15.080 --> 24:18.360
"When I go back to England,
I want to own my own pub."

24:21.360 --> 24:22.840
Well.

24:26.440 --> 24:27.920
Now you've gone soft.

24:28.800 --> 24:30.560
You've gone soft, Tommy.

24:33.160 --> 24:35.000
How do we know it's for sale?

24:35.400 --> 24:37.440
Everything is for sale to us, Arthur.

24:38.960 --> 24:41.160
We're making a lot of money these days.

24:41.680 --> 24:43.360
We need a legitimate business

24:43.600 --> 24:45.720
to pass the money from the shop.

24:46.680 --> 24:48.600
I wouldn't know what to do.

24:49.320 --> 24:53.040
You spent two-thirds of your life
in pubs, just pour it.

24:53.320 --> 24:55.120
Instead of drinking it.

24:56.200 --> 24:57.920
But I can still drink it though, right?

24:58.000 --> 25:00.360
Your pub, you do what you want.

25:03.560 --> 25:06.160
Ah. Sorry, gentlemen.

25:06.720 --> 25:08.120
Didn't hear you come in.

25:08.800 --> 25:10.120
What can I get you?

25:29.560 --> 25:30.920
MOSS: Bloody kids.

25:31.600 --> 25:33.240
Think the other one's punctured as well.

25:35.840 --> 25:37.760
Mr Campbell wants an explanation.

25:38.560 --> 25:39.680
Today,

25:39.760 --> 25:43.760
some rebel-rousing union man
brought the BSA out on strike.

25:45.880 --> 25:47.360
Freddie Thorne.

25:48.600 --> 25:50.440
I thought you promised
he wouldn't come back.

25:50.800 --> 25:52.160
I know he's in town.

25:52.240 --> 25:53.520
I'm dealing with it.

25:53.640 --> 25:57.160
Mr Campbell thought that
you controlled these territories.

25:57.560 --> 25:58.640
Yeah.

26:00.120 --> 26:02.000
I said I'm dealing with it.

26:03.520 --> 26:05.320
I heard that, er,

26:06.720 --> 26:08.400
Freddie married your sister.

26:09.240 --> 26:10.920
Some family you've got, eh?

26:11.320 --> 26:13.000
Bet you can't wait for Christmas.

26:15.240 --> 26:17.000
Deliver Freddie Thorne to us,

26:18.240 --> 26:20.800
or we'll take your sister in
as an accomplice.

26:21.240 --> 26:23.560
She'll get four years for sedition.

26:25.560 --> 26:27.320
Or you can turn him in.

26:27.880 --> 26:29.600
And your sister goes free.

26:37.240 --> 26:39.400
I'll say goodnight then, Tom.

26:52.960 --> 26:54.360
(PANTING)

27:06.240 --> 27:07.600
ADA: Have you seen Freddie Thorne?

27:07.960 --> 27:10.000
-No.
-Or Tommy? (GROANS)

27:25.800 --> 27:27.840
-ADA: We have to find Freddie.
-Drink this first.

27:27.920 --> 27:30.000
No, we have to find them.
I think they're gonna kill each other.

27:30.080 --> 27:32.120
Wait. Who's going to kill who?

27:34.080 --> 27:35.320
We need to talk.

27:42.360 --> 27:44.400
What exactly is it
that you want, Freddie?

27:46.320 --> 27:48.000
I came to tell you.

27:51.240 --> 27:53.000
That's not gonna work, Tommy.

27:55.400 --> 27:56.840
Polly came round.

27:57.680 --> 27:59.040
She gave me that.

28:01.120 --> 28:02.320
Well,

28:02.400 --> 28:04.560
Polly must've had a rush of blood.

28:04.960 --> 28:06.800
Or port wine.

28:07.560 --> 28:10.440
Your honesty is appreciated. Now,
if you're not gonna use that thing...

28:10.520 --> 28:11.640
I'm not finished!

28:12.560 --> 28:13.760
Sit down.

28:14.320 --> 28:16.240
Sit down. Sit!

28:21.840 --> 28:23.560
Talk to me about the guns.

28:26.000 --> 28:29.120
Do you remember we used to jump
in here and see who could swim across...

28:29.200 --> 28:31.400
I'm here to talk business, Tommy.

28:34.040 --> 28:35.840
Do you reckon we could still do it?

28:39.800 --> 28:40.880
(GRUNTING)

28:43.360 --> 28:44.880
(BOTH PANTING)

28:50.440 --> 28:52.800
You loaded Ada with your bastard

28:53.200 --> 28:54.880
because she's a Shelby.

28:55.920 --> 28:58.360
You thought it'd mean you'd be somebody.

29:00.160 --> 29:03.440
I won't let you fuck up my sister's life
for your cause.

29:08.080 --> 29:09.720
My God,

29:14.280 --> 29:16.360
you actually believe that?

29:22.960 --> 29:24.360
I love her, Tommy.

29:26.080 --> 29:28.720
I've loved her since she was nine
and I was twelve.

29:30.680 --> 29:32.680
She loves me the same.

29:40.760 --> 29:42.760
Do you even know the word?

29:46.080 --> 29:48.320
This marriage will not stand.

29:49.600 --> 29:52.480
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

29:58.560 --> 30:00.080
Shh.

30:05.640 --> 30:06.960
(SIGHS)

30:20.040 --> 30:21.920
Freddie

30:22.000 --> 30:23.680
didn't want your money.

30:24.320 --> 30:27.640
And now the coppers are saying that
if we don't turn Freddie in,

30:27.720 --> 30:29.720
they'll put Ada
on the arrest warrant as well.

30:30.600 --> 30:32.880
That's where your compassion
gets you, Pol.

30:33.760 --> 30:36.240
From now on, we do it my way.

30:37.640 --> 30:39.000
Or what?

30:43.080 --> 30:44.320
(SIGHS)

30:51.720 --> 30:53.320
(PANTING)

30:58.360 --> 30:59.960
(EXHALES)

31:17.000 --> 31:18.680
Freddie?

31:19.680 --> 31:21.560
TOMMY: <i>Are you getting closer?</i>

31:25.240 --> 31:26.520
DANNY: I'll lead.

31:26.600 --> 31:29.360
FREDDIE: Watch yourself, Danny.
DANNY: Tommy.

31:30.640 --> 31:32.120
(METAL CREAKS)

31:35.240 --> 31:36.760
(LAMP RATTLES)

31:36.840 --> 31:38.560
TOMMY: <i>Be careful, Danny.</i>

31:40.120 --> 31:42.040
(HEAVY BREATHING)

31:42.560 --> 31:44.760
(TAPPING)

31:51.160 --> 31:53.800
(WHISPERING IN GERMAN)

31:56.520 --> 31:58.800
(WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY IN GERMAN)

32:00.440 --> 32:03.440
(WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY IN GERMAN)

32:03.640 --> 32:05.000
MAN: Shh, shh.

32:06.000 --> 32:09.000
-(GRUNTS)
-(SCREAMS)

32:10.440 --> 32:12.640
-(SHOUTING) Tommy!
-(GUN SHOT)

32:13.240 --> 32:15.880
-(SCREAMING)
-(STRAINING)

32:21.960 --> 32:23.280
(SCREAMING)

32:24.680 --> 32:26.200
-MAN: Tommy!
-(KNOCKING <i>AT</i> DOOR)

32:26.360 --> 32:28.160
-(PANTING)
-DANNY: Tommy.

32:29.360 --> 32:32.800
-Tommy. Tommy.
-(KEYS JANGLING)

32:38.080 --> 32:39.520
(SIGHS)

32:40.040 --> 32:41.120
It's open.

32:47.240 --> 32:49.160
Private Whizz-Bang reporting, sir.

32:49.440 --> 32:51.160
(CHUCKLES) At ease.

33:05.240 --> 33:07.720
So, what news from London?

33:08.480 --> 33:09.840
I was in a pub.

33:10.400 --> 33:13.400
It was called The Mother Red Cap.
An Irish pub.

33:14.440 --> 33:16.880
I got talking to
some old bloke about Birmingham.

33:18.080 --> 33:19.320
He said there's been trouble.

33:19.640 --> 33:21.160
An IRA man shot.

33:22.680 --> 33:25.040
He said a lot, but the only bit I heard

33:25.120 --> 33:27.840
was that their high command think
it's the Peaky Blinders who shot him.

33:29.920 --> 33:31.600
I came up on the next boat to warn you.

33:33.680 --> 33:34.880
Is it true?

33:36.160 --> 33:37.760
No.

33:38.480 --> 33:41.640
-But lies travel faster than the truth.
-Hmm.

33:43.720 --> 33:45.200
Get a message to them.

33:46.200 --> 33:48.400
Tell 'em to send someone to parlay.

33:48.640 --> 33:51.960
Tell 'em there's been a misunderstanding
and we don't want any trouble.

33:55.400 --> 33:57.680
You've got enough trouble, right, Tommy?

33:59.360 --> 34:02.240
The whisky and the smoke.

34:07.600 --> 34:09.560
I can smell it in the air.

34:10.200 --> 34:11.520
(SIGHS)

34:12.560 --> 34:14.480
Use it sometimes myself.

34:15.520 --> 34:18.600
-Call it my sweetheart.
-(CHUCKLES)

34:20.600 --> 34:22.720
They gave us the worst job, Tommy.

34:23.760 --> 34:26.320
Yeah... (HUFFS)

34:26.400 --> 34:28.160
And we fucking volunteered.

34:28.240 --> 34:29.520
(CHUCKLING)

34:42.640 --> 34:44.760
Sometimes it lasts all night.

34:47.520 --> 34:49.200
And I lie here

34:49.840 --> 34:52.480
and I listen to the shovels...

34:52.560 --> 34:54.440
And the picks

34:54.520 --> 34:56.440
against that wall there.

35:00.680 --> 35:04.640
And I pray the sun will come up with
the curtains before they break through.

35:07.360 --> 35:08.960
TOMMY: <i>No, I don't pray.</i>

35:09.600 --> 35:10.680
<i>I hope.</i>

35:12.680 --> 35:15.400
<i>-But sometimes it happens.</i>
-(DIGGING)

35:15.480 --> 35:17.320
<i>The sun beats them.</i>

35:18.360 --> 35:19.960
<i>But mostly...</i>

35:20.040 --> 35:21.880
(DIGGING)

35:22.960 --> 35:25.320
<i>The shovels beat the sun.</i>

35:26.080 --> 35:28.200
(DIGGING CONTINUES)

35:28.760 --> 35:30.400
(CRUMBLING)

36:13.080 --> 36:14.720
(SIGHS)

36:28.600 --> 36:30.080
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

36:46.040 --> 36:47.440
Your sister was here.

36:48.960 --> 36:50.320
(SIGHS)

36:52.440 --> 36:54.040
GRACE: She was worried
you and Freddie...

36:55.400 --> 36:56.720
It had made her sick.

36:58.960 --> 37:01.800
She's all right,
but in her condition she needs peace.

37:03.520 --> 37:04.840
Women talk.

37:04.920 --> 37:06.360
That is something they do.

37:08.840 --> 37:10.040
She talked about you.

37:12.720 --> 37:14.240
She said you keep everything locked up.

37:15.840 --> 37:17.240
Well...

37:17.320 --> 37:18.920
That's what men do.

37:19.680 --> 37:21.040
Your sister's nice. I like her.

37:22.280 --> 37:23.800
Can't be easy for her.

37:24.160 --> 37:26.360
Her brother and her husband
fighting over the same thing.

37:32.120 --> 37:34.160
Men should talk too.

37:35.040 --> 37:36.320
To you?

37:39.080 --> 37:40.320
Why not?

37:40.640 --> 37:42.360
I'm a barmaid. It's my job.

37:43.160 --> 37:45.520
Men always tell their troubles
to a barmaid.

37:47.120 --> 37:49.800
What is it you and Freddie
are fighting over?

38:00.360 --> 38:01.440
(SIGHS)

38:02.520 --> 38:05.320
I'll meet you here at 9:00
tomorrow morning.

38:09.080 --> 38:10.240
Did you buy a dress?

38:11.320 --> 38:13.560
Yes, I bought a dress.

38:14.320 --> 38:15.720
How does it look?

39:32.720 --> 39:33.760
(TRAIN CHUGGING)

39:33.840 --> 39:35.760
CHARLIE: He's changed the oil
and greased her up.

39:36.720 --> 39:39.200
So will it get me all the way
to Cheltenham, Curly?

39:39.600 --> 39:41.640
He's good with motors but it pains him.

39:42.080 --> 39:44.480
No heart in motor cars.
I can't talk to them.

39:44.560 --> 39:47.560
Yeah... Tommy might need
to make a fast getaway.

39:48.320 --> 39:50.240
The Lees will be all over the track.

39:50.320 --> 39:52.160
And Kimber's men.

39:52.240 --> 39:54.480
And his coppers, they control the law
down there, Tommy.

39:54.560 --> 39:56.200
Give 'er a turn for me, Charlie.

39:57.760 --> 40:00.000
(ENGINE STARTING)

40:03.720 --> 40:05.600
This car only seats four.

40:05.680 --> 40:08.040
You'll need more men than that
if you're to come back alive.

40:08.480 --> 40:09.760
But it's just me and the girl.

40:19.560 --> 40:21.920
Is it just the two of us
going to the races?

40:22.000 --> 40:23.320
Something like that.

40:57.880 --> 40:59.600
Attention!

41:00.080 --> 41:01.720
-ARTHUR: Right.
-(THUDDING)

41:01.880 --> 41:06.440
This is what's known as your final
briefing before going over the top.

41:06.520 --> 41:09.160
Sixty miles down that road
is Cheltenham race track.

41:09.480 --> 41:11.920
Johnny, what's our mission, boy?

41:12.000 --> 41:15.040
To stick it to the Lee family, Arthur!

41:15.240 --> 41:16.600
That's right.

41:16.680 --> 41:19.240
The Lees are skimming money
off legal bookies,

41:19.760 --> 41:22.280
running chalk, selling rafflers.

41:22.520 --> 41:24.280
And beating up them as won't buy.

41:24.720 --> 41:25.960
But, today...

41:26.640 --> 41:29.360
-We're gonna stop them.
-What about Kimber's men?

41:29.440 --> 41:31.040
Thought he had his own protection.

41:31.120 --> 41:33.280
Kimber's let his troops go rotten.

41:34.280 --> 41:37.280
They're on the take from the Lees
to look the other way.

41:38.440 --> 41:40.720
We're gonna show Kimber
how it should be done.

41:41.320 --> 41:42.760
Now take what you're good at.

41:43.040 --> 41:45.760
Those of you with guns,
keep them out of it

41:45.840 --> 41:48.480
unless a gun is pulled on you.
We want this done quietly.

41:52.080 --> 41:53.960
MAN: So when do we share out the cash?

41:54.040 --> 41:56.760
We don't. We're not keeping the cash.

41:57.240 --> 41:59.520
You're in Tommy's army now, boys.

42:00.160 --> 42:01.800
Trust only kin.

42:03.560 --> 42:05.200
Let's go.

42:06.080 --> 42:08.600
(THUDDING)

42:11.800 --> 42:13.400
(ENGINE WHIRRING)

42:20.000 --> 42:22.600
(TRACK ANNOUNCER TALKING
INDISTINCTLY OVER SPEAKER)

42:22.720 --> 42:24.880
MAN 1 : What stable's he?
MAN 2: Number seven, isn't it?

42:24.960 --> 42:26.880
Are you sure we're allowed in here?

42:26.960 --> 42:29.640
Well, I prefer to come to the races
the back way.

42:30.040 --> 42:32.080
Keeps me out of trouble.

42:32.160 --> 42:34.280
Tracks are lawless places.

42:34.360 --> 42:37.040
Can't stand petty criminals. This way.

42:37.120 --> 42:38.320
Will we get to lay a bet?

42:38.400 --> 42:40.520
Nah. Gambling's for mugs.

42:40.600 --> 42:42.360
This way.

42:42.680 --> 42:43.840
You're lucky you're with me

42:43.920 --> 42:46.240
or you'd be wasting your money
on fixed races.

42:46.320 --> 42:48.800
I always wondered,
how do you fix a race?

42:48.880 --> 42:50.560
How should I know?

42:52.720 --> 42:55.920
-Okay. You do the talking.
-What?

42:56.240 --> 42:59.360
Tell security you are Lady Sarah...

42:59.440 --> 43:01.560
TOMMY: Excuse us. Excuse us.

43:01.640 --> 43:03.880
Lady Sarah Duggan of Connemara.

43:03.960 --> 43:06.800
You got lost when you went
to look for the boy riding your horse.

43:06.880 --> 43:10.160
Uh, Dandy Flower. If they ask about me,
say that I'm Prussian.

43:10.240 --> 43:12.120
Don't speak a word of English.

43:12.560 --> 43:14.800
Come on, posh girl.
Earn your three quid.

43:20.800 --> 43:22.600
(JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

43:45.680 --> 43:47.280
I still prefer The Garrison.

43:51.120 --> 43:52.520
Do you dance?

43:53.480 --> 43:55.280
If I am asked properly.

43:57.400 --> 43:59.840
Lady Sarah of Connemara,

43:59.920 --> 44:01.680
will you dance with me?

44:07.440 --> 44:09.560
(MUSIC CONTINUES)

45:00.200 --> 45:02.680
Roberts, the Peaky Blinders are here.

45:03.560 --> 45:04.960
Told you, Mr Kimber.

45:05.160 --> 45:06.800
He's got some balls, that one.

45:06.880 --> 45:08.920
And she's got some body, that one.

45:21.600 --> 45:24.000
-(GROANS)
-Chalk. For your blackboard.

45:24.200 --> 45:25.880
Five pound a stick.

45:29.960 --> 45:32.080
It's a pleasure doing business with you.

45:34.040 --> 45:35.400
(GROANING)

45:36.480 --> 45:38.960
Hello, Reg. How's business?

45:39.160 --> 45:41.120
(GROANING)

45:41.600 --> 45:43.840
(BANGING)

45:44.880 --> 45:47.040
-Fucker, get up!
-(PANTING)

45:48.960 --> 45:50.480
(GRUNTS)

45:52.120 --> 45:53.760
(SCREAMS)

45:56.120 --> 45:59.600
Stay still, Reg, or I'll take
the whole ear off.

45:59.680 --> 46:01.440
And you're gonna need
your ears to listen.

46:02.240 --> 46:05.560
No more chalking on Billy Kimber's boys.

46:05.840 --> 46:08.040
-Right?
-(PANTING)

46:08.280 --> 46:10.320
We're the protection now.

46:12.440 --> 46:15.000
I commandeer this stolen money,

46:15.360 --> 46:19.000
by order of the Peaky Blinders.

46:19.320 --> 46:21.160
(GROANS)

46:22.920 --> 46:24.080
(SPITS)

46:24.360 --> 46:27.360
(TRACK ANNOUNCER TALKING
INDISTINCTLY OVER SPEAKER)

46:27.520 --> 46:29.000
(PANTING)

46:45.960 --> 46:47.880
Either your left leg is stronger
than your right

46:47.960 --> 46:49.160
or we're making a getaway.

46:49.240 --> 46:51.120
MAN: Hey!
TOMMY: Neither.

46:51.280 --> 46:53.360
GRACE: I hope this doesn't involve
razor blades.

46:53.440 --> 46:55.480
I've decided to move up in the world.

46:55.560 --> 46:57.320
Become a legitimate businessman.

46:57.680 --> 46:58.920
My gosh, you're serious.

46:59.520 --> 47:01.840
I'm always serious.

47:04.000 --> 47:05.360
We chased the Lees across the track

47:05.440 --> 47:07.280
right the way down the Devon Road.

47:07.360 --> 47:09.080
We got every penny back.

47:09.160 --> 47:11.280
(PANTING) Nice dress.

47:11.360 --> 47:12.840
You can wear that in my pub.

47:13.120 --> 47:15.400
Buy the boys a drink. Anyone hurt?

47:15.480 --> 47:16.880
Ah... <i>A</i> few cuts and bruises.

47:17.760 --> 47:19.280
Off we go, Lady Sarah.

47:26.480 --> 47:27.720
Steady on.

47:28.160 --> 47:30.040
TOMMY: Excuse me.
MAN: Cheers.

47:33.760 --> 47:35.280
(COINS CLINKING)

47:37.360 --> 47:38.880
TOMMY: Your money, Mr Kimber.

47:40.240 --> 47:42.440
Rescued from the Lee brothers

47:42.520 --> 47:46.040
and returned to you
with a request for a fair hearing.

47:47.320 --> 47:49.800
Your own protection is failing,
Mr Kimber.

47:50.560 --> 47:52.760
Your boys are taking cuts.

47:53.600 --> 47:55.880
I want to suggest that from now on,

47:55.960 --> 47:59.800
you contract out your racetrack security
to the Peaky Blinders.

48:00.800 --> 48:03.000
We'd be saving you
a lot of money, Mr Kimber.

48:03.680 --> 48:05.080
Lot of money.

48:05.240 --> 48:07.840
-In return, you give us...
-(MATCH STRIKING)

48:08.960 --> 48:10.920
Five percent of the take

48:11.400 --> 48:13.440
and three legal betting pitches

48:13.520 --> 48:15.760
at every race meeting
north of the River Severn.

48:15.960 --> 48:20.200
Rising to six after one year
if we're all satisfied with the service.

48:22.640 --> 48:24.280
What do you say, Mr Kimber?

48:29.000 --> 48:31.440
I say you talk business
to my accountant.

48:31.800 --> 48:33.560
I want a dance.

48:45.040 --> 48:47.600
Your man said it was all right
for me to have this dance.

49:10.320 --> 49:12.920
How many men can you put
in the field at one time?

49:13.640 --> 49:15.520
TOMMY: There's a lot of men
out of work at the moment.

49:16.240 --> 49:18.000
Two guards for every bookie.

49:18.080 --> 49:19.760
ROBERTS: At every meeting.

49:21.080 --> 49:24.120
We have contacts with good people
among the gypsies.

49:24.200 --> 49:26.960
(CLEARING THROAT) We'll always know
when the Lees plan to attack.

49:27.840 --> 49:30.080
With all the strikes and troubles,

49:30.160 --> 49:32.320
can't really depend on the police.

49:32.400 --> 49:34.880
Anyway, we're more honest.

49:36.520 --> 49:37.920
Looks like you two are making a deal.

49:38.280 --> 49:39.600
We are making progress.

49:41.560 --> 49:44.280
Then let me throw
a small condition into the mix.

50:01.040 --> 50:02.640
So, listen, uh...

50:02.720 --> 50:05.040
We're gonna go for dinner
at Kimber's house.

50:05.120 --> 50:07.360
He has a place a couple of miles away.

50:07.680 --> 50:10.480
I have some business to settle first
with his accountant, so...

50:10.760 --> 50:12.840
You go on ahead with Kimber.

50:14.000 --> 50:15.520
Just me and him?

50:15.680 --> 50:18.320
Yeah. Till I'm done here.

50:18.720 --> 50:19.920
Is that all right?

50:22.320 --> 50:26.000
Look, I'll throw in an extra three quid
for your extra time.

50:28.040 --> 50:29.520
You think I'm a whore.

50:30.040 --> 50:31.280
(SIGHS)

50:31.560 --> 50:34.360
Everyone's a whore, Grace.

50:34.440 --> 50:36.600
We just sell different parts
of ourselves.

50:37.080 --> 50:38.960
You said you wanted to work for me.

50:39.040 --> 50:40.840
To do that you have to sharpen up.

50:40.920 --> 50:43.120
The deal is, I'll give him
two hours with you.

50:43.880 --> 50:45.720
He thinks he's a ladies' man.

50:45.800 --> 50:47.320
He thinks he can seduce you.

50:47.400 --> 50:49.760
Whenever you want,
just kick him in the balls.

50:49.840 --> 50:51.600
I'm a clause in a contract.

50:51.680 --> 50:55.320
If you wanna be part of my organisation,
you have to make sacrifices.

50:59.440 --> 51:02.440
Do we have a deal? As a sweetener,
you can try your luck with mine.

51:04.440 --> 51:05.840
Yeah, we have a deal.

51:05.920 --> 51:07.720
-Two hours?
-Yeah.

51:07.800 --> 51:10.480
Side bet,10 pounds says
I'll have her fucked in one.

51:13.000 --> 51:14.360
KIMBER: Mademoiselle.

51:24.840 --> 51:26.640
I bet he said you could have me,
didn't he?

51:29.000 --> 51:30.440
While he has her.

51:31.040 --> 51:32.680
That's the arrangement, isn't it?

51:36.480 --> 51:38.680
Yours might be a prostitute,
but I'm not.

51:40.120 --> 51:41.920
I was a milliner when I met him.

51:43.160 --> 51:44.800
I was independent.

51:47.640 --> 51:49.680
I made this hat.

51:50.480 --> 51:52.080
I was a good milliner.

51:53.160 --> 51:55.120
It's a very pretty hat.

51:56.920 --> 51:58.560
Really is.

52:08.400 --> 52:10.240
So is she a prostitute?

52:11.880 --> 52:13.600
(SIGHING) God's honest truth,

52:14.280 --> 52:15.960
I don't know what she is.

52:19.600 --> 52:21.160
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

52:25.120 --> 52:27.920
You showed me up
back there at the races.

52:28.000 --> 52:29.720
(MUSIC PLAYING)

52:31.040 --> 52:33.880
Why don't you teach me
how to dance properly?

52:35.080 --> 52:37.760
The music's too slow.
Put on a Charleston.

52:37.920 --> 52:40.520
Well, then we'd be far away.
I want to dance like this.

52:42.320 --> 52:45.480
Come on, you weren't so stiff
back there, were you? Hmm?

52:47.000 --> 52:48.920
You ever been in a house this big?

52:50.440 --> 52:51.760
Hmm?

52:52.480 --> 52:54.160
Mmm. Look at you.

52:57.080 --> 52:59.520
You look like a bloody film star.

53:01.160 --> 53:02.520
(GASPS)

53:04.080 --> 53:05.760
I want a cigarette.

53:15.920 --> 53:18.120
-(GLASS SHATTERING)
-Oh, look, I've dropped something.

53:18.320 --> 53:19.880
Pick it up.

53:19.960 --> 53:22.200
-Pick it up yourself.
-You're a fucking barmaid.

53:22.280 --> 53:24.480
If I drop a glass on the floor,
you pick it up.

53:24.560 --> 53:26.280
I want to watch you pick it up.

53:30.400 --> 53:32.520
-(GLASS CRUNCHING)
-Right, you little slag.

53:32.680 --> 53:35.520
-I tried to be nice. Yeah?
-(GROANS)

53:35.600 --> 53:38.800
If I drop a glass on the floor,

53:39.240 --> 53:43.400
you bend over and fucking pick up
the fucking glass.

53:43.480 --> 53:45.720
-Okay? (SHOUTING) What?
-No, sir. No.

53:45.800 --> 53:47.320
KIMBER: What are you doing here?

53:47.400 --> 53:49.520
-I've got another hour.
-TOMMY: Just wait.

53:49.600 --> 53:52.440
Listen to me. Just listen to me.

53:52.880 --> 53:55.440
I was going to let you go through
with this but, in the end,

53:55.520 --> 53:59.520
my conscience got the better of me.
She looks good on the outside,

54:01.960 --> 54:03.760
but she has the clap.

54:06.200 --> 54:08.080
TOMMY: Yeah. Syphilis.

54:09.440 --> 54:11.080
When you took a shine to her,
I thought I'd use her.

54:11.280 --> 54:13.800
Someone told me she had the syph,
I thought, "What the hell?"

54:16.560 --> 54:18.560
Call it my better nature.

54:19.400 --> 54:21.040
She's, uh, she's a whore.

54:26.560 --> 54:29.480
-Well, just go and wait in the car.
-I can walk on my own.

54:34.560 --> 54:36.600
Can we shake hands
and forget this ever happened?

54:44.000 --> 54:45.760
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

54:48.000 --> 54:49.920
(GATE CREAKING)

55:01.680 --> 55:04.400
Start of the day,
I was Lady Sarah of Connemara.

55:05.960 --> 55:09.040
By the end, I was a whore with the clap.

55:11.160 --> 55:13.600
You're a fucking bastard,
offering me like that.

55:19.560 --> 55:21.600
But then you change your mind.

55:25.440 --> 55:27.360
Why did you change your mind, Thomas?

55:32.720 --> 55:34.720
(THEME SONG PLAYING)

55:49.520 --> 55:55.200
<i># Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track</i>

55:57.160 --> 56:01.280
<i># Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

56:01.360 --> 56:05.360
<i># As it shifts and cracks... #</i>

56:05.384 --> 56:10.384
http://hiqve.com/
